Description: CVE-2026-53615 - libblkid: dos: validate EBR data and links within extended partition
 The parse_dos_extended() function in libblkid processes EBR (Extended Boot
 Record) chains, but does not properly validate that partitions and links
 stay within the master extended partition area [ex_start, ex_start+ex_size).
 .
 For EBR data partitions at index 0 and 1, there are no bounds checks at all,
 unlike entries at index 2 and 3. A crafted disk image (e.g. cur_start=2 and
 lba_start=0xFFFFFFFE) can register partitions at arbitrary sectors via
 uint32_t overflow in the abs_start = cur_start + start computation (the sum
 wraps to a small value such as 0, i.e. the MBR itself). Consumers such as
 udisks2, blkid, and mkfs treat this as a legitimate partition offset, which
 can overwrite the partition table and render the disk unbootable (CWE-190).
 .
 Fix by:
  - using 64-bit arithmetic for offset calculations to avoid uint32_t
    wraparound (upstream commit ab43959);
  - applying the extended partition area bounds check to all EBR data
    entries, not just index >= 2;
  - validating EBR link targets stay within the extended area and advance
    forward (preventing backward links that could loop).
 .
 This is a combination of upstream commits e9d544d ("libblkid: dos: validate
 EBR data and links within extended partition") and ab43959 ("libblkid: dos:
 use 64-bit for partition offset calculations"), both by Karel Zak. Also
 cherry-picked on the stable/v2.41 branch as 05c2dba.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/util-linux/util-linux/commit/e9d544d013267ea86b70ee8ff78abd280e6641af
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/util-linux/util-linux/commit/ab43959005b9d1f9e538c30e63dfc2827049af04
Author: Karel Zak <kzak@redhat.com>
